[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The core of Apache Hadoop consists of a storage part, known as Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), and a processing part which is a MapReduce programming model.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Hadoop splits files into large blocks and distributes them across nodes in a cluster.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] It then transfers packaged code into nodes to process the data in parallel.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] This approach takes advantage of data locality, where nodes manipulate the data they have access to.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] This allows the dataset to be processed faster and more efficiently than it would be in a more conventional supercomputer architecture that relies on a parallel file system where computation and data are distributed via high-speed networking.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Apache Hadoop's MapReduce and HDFS components were inspired by Google papers on MapReduce and Google File System.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop framework itself is mostly written in the Java programming language, with some native code in C and command line utilities written as shell scripts.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Perl language can be easily used with Hadoop Streaming to implement the map and reduce parts of the user's program.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] According to its co-founders, Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella, the idea of Hadoop was conceived in the Google File System paper that was published in October 2003.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The concept was extended in the Google paper *"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters".* Development started on the Apache Nutch project, but was moved to the new Hadoop subproject in January 2006.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Doug Cutting, who was working at Yahoo! at the time, named it after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The initial code that was factored out of Nutch consisted of about 5,000 lines of code for HDFS and about 6,000 lines of code for MapReduce.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] In March 2006, Owen O'Malley was the first committer to add to the Hadoop project; Hadoop 0.1.0 was released in April 2006.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] It continues to evolve through contributions that are being made to the project.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The first design document for the Hadoop Distributed File System was written by Dhruba Borthakur in 2007.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Hadoop consists of the *Hadoop Common* package, which provides file system and operating system level abstractions, a MapReduce engine (either MapReduce/MR1 or YARN/MR2) and the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop Common package contains the Java Archive (JAR) files and scripts needed to start Hadoop.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] For effective scheduling of work, every Hadoop-compatible file system should provide location awareness, which is the name of the rack, specifically the network switch where a worker node is.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Hadoop applications can use this information to execute code on the node where the data is, and, failing that, on the same rack/switch to reduce backbone traffic.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] HDFS uses this method when replicating data for data redundancy across multiple racks.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] This approach reduces the impact of a rack power outage or switch failure; if any of these hardware failures occurs, the data will remain available.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] A small Hadoop cluster includes a single master and multiple worker nodes.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The master node consists of a Job Tracker, Task Tracker, NameNode, and DataNode.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] A slave or *worker node* acts as both a DataNode and TaskTracker, though it is possible to have data-only and compute-only worker nodes.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] These are normally used only in nonstandard applications.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Hadoop requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 1.6 or higher.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The standard startup and shutdown scripts require that Secure Shell (SSH) be set up between nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] In a larger cluster, HDFS nodes are managed through a dedicated NameNode server to host the file system index, and a secondary NameNode that can generate snapshots of the namenode's memory structures, thereby preventing file-system corruption and loss of data.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Similarly, a standalone JobTracker server can manage job scheduling across nodes.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop MapReduce is used with an alternate file system, the NameNode, secondary NameNode, and DataNode architecture of HDFS are replaced by the file-system-specific equivalents.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The *Hadoop distributed file system* (HDFS) is a distributed, scalable, and portable file system written in Java for the Hadoop framework.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] A Hadoop instance is divided into HDFS and MapReduce.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] HDFS is used for storing the data and MapReduce is used for processing data.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Top three are Master Services/Daemons/Nodes and bottom two are Slave Services.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Master Services can communicate with each other and in the same way Slave services can communicate with each other.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Name Node is a master node and Data node is its corresponding Slave node and can talk with each other.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Hadoop cluster has nominally a single namenode plus a cluster of datanodes, although redundancy options are available for the namenode due to its criticality.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Each datanode serves up blocks of data over the network using a block protocol specific to HDFS.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The file system uses TCP/IP sockets for communication.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Clients use remote procedure calls (RPC) to communicate with each other.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] HDFS stores large files (typically in the range of gigabytes to terabytes) across multiple machines.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] It achieves reliability by replicating the data across multiple hosts, and hence theoretically does not require redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage on hosts (but to increase input-output (I/O) performance some RAID configurations are still useful).
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] With the default replication value, 3, data is stored on three nodes: two on the same rack, and one on a different rack.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Data nodes can talk to each other to rebalance data, to move copies around, and to keep the replication of data high.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] HDFS is not fully POSIX-compliant, because the requirements for a POSIX file-system differ from the target goals of a Hadoop application.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The trade-off of not having a fully POSIX-compliant file-system is increased performance for data throughput and support for non-POSIX operations such as Append.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] In May 2012, high-availability capabilities were added to HDFS, letting the main metadata server called the NameNode manually fail-over onto a backup.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The project has also started developing automatic fail-overs.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The HDFS file system includes a so-called *secondary namenode*, a misleading term that some might incorrectly interpret as a backup namenode when the primary namenode goes offline.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] In fact, the secondary namenode regularly connects with the primary namenode and builds snapshots of the primary namenode's directory information, which the system then saves to local or remote directories.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] These checkpointed images can be used to restart a failed primary namenode without having to replay the entire journal of file-system actions, then to edit the log to create an up-to-date directory structure.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Because the namenode is the single point for storage and management of metadata, it can become a bottleneck for supporting a huge number of files, especially a large number of small files.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] HDFS Federation, a new addition, aims to tackle this problem to a certain extent by allowing multiple namespaces served by separate namenodes.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Moreover, there are some issues in HDFS such as small file issues, scalability problems, Single Point of Failure (SPoF), and bottlenecks in huge metadata requests.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] One advantage of using HDFS is data awareness between the job tracker and task tracker.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The job tracker schedules map or reduce jobs to task trackers with an awareness of the data location.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] For example: if node A contains data (a, b, c) and node X contains data (x, y, z), the job tracker schedules node A to perform map or reduce tasks on (a, b, c) and node X would be scheduled to perform map or reduce tasks on (x, y, z).
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] This reduces the amount of traffic that goes over the network and prevents unnecessary data transfer.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop is used with other file systems, this advantage is not always available.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] This can have a significant impact on job-completion times as demonstrated with data-intensive jobs.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] HDFS was designed for mostly immutable files and may not be suitable for systems requiring concurrent write operations.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] HDFS can be mounted directly with a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) virtual file system on Linux and some other Unix systems.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] File access can be achieved through the native Java API, the Thrift API (generates a client in a number of languages e.g.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] C++, Java, Python, PHP, Ruby, Erlang, Perl, Haskell, C#, Cocoa, Smalltalk, and OCaml), the command-line interface, the HDFS-UI web application over HTTP, or via 3rd-party network client libraries.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] HDFS is designed for portability across various hardware platforms and for compatibility with a variety of underlying operating systems.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The HDFS design introduces portability limitations that result in some performance bottlenecks, since the Java implementation cannot use features that are exclusive to the platform on which HDFS is running.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Due to its widespread integration into enterprise-level infrastructure, monitoring HDFS performance at scale has become an increasingly important issue.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Monitoring end-to-end performance requires tracking metrics from datanodes, namenodes, and the underlying operating system.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] There are currently several monitoring platforms to track HDFS performance, including Hortonworks, Cloudera, and Datadog.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Hadoop works directly with any distributed file system that can be mounted by the underlying operating system by simply using a `file://` URL; however, this comes at a price – the loss of locality.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] To reduce network traffic, Hadoop needs to know which servers are closest to the data, information that Hadoop-specific file system bridges can provide.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] A number of third-party file system bridges have also been written, none of which are currently in Hadoop distributions.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] However, some commercial distributions of Hadoop ship with an alternative file system as the default – specifically IBM and MapR.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Atop the file systems comes the MapReduce Engine, which consists of one *JobTracker*, to which client applications submit MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The JobTracker pushes work to available *TaskTracker* nodes in the cluster, striving to keep the work as close to the data as possible.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] With a rack-aware file system, the JobTracker knows which node contains the data, and which other machines are nearby.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] If the work cannot be hosted on the actual node where the data resides, priority is given to nodes in the same rack.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] This reduces network traffic on the main backbone network.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] If a TaskTracker fails or times out, that part of the job is rescheduled.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The TaskTracker on each node spawns a separate Java virtual machine (JVM) process to prevent the TaskTracker itself from failing if the running job crashes its JVM.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] A heartbeat is sent from the TaskTracker to the JobTracker every few minutes to check its status.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The Job Tracker and TaskTracker status and information is exposed by Jetty and can be viewed from a web browser.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] If one TaskTracker is very slow, it can delay the entire MapReduce job – especially towards the end, when everything can end up waiting for the slowest task.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] With speculative execution enabled, however, a single task can be executed on multiple slave nodes.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] By default Hadoop uses FIFO scheduling, and optionally 5 scheduling priorities to schedule jobs from a work queue.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] In version 0.19 the job scheduler was refactored out of the JobTracker, while adding the ability to use an alternate scheduler (such as the *Fair scheduler* or the *Capacity scheduler*, described next).
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler was developed by Facebook.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The goal of the fair scheduler is to provide fast response times for small jobs and quality of service (QoS) for production jobs.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler has three basic concepts.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Each pool is assigned a guaranteed minimum share.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] By default, jobs that are uncategorized go into a default pool.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Pools have to specify the minimum number of map slots, reduce slots, as well as a limit on the number of running jobs.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler was developed by Yahoo.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler supports several features that are similar to those of the fair scheduler.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Free resources are allocated to queues beyond their total capacity.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Within a queue, a job with a high level of priority has access to the queue's resources.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] There is no preemption once a job is running.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The biggest difference between Hadoop 1 and Hadoop 2 is the addition of YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator), which replaced the MapReduce engine in the first version of Hadoop.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] YARN strives to allocate resources to various applications effectively.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] It runs two daemons, which take care of two different tasks: the *resource manager*, which does job tracking and resource allocation to applications, the *application master*, which monitors progress of the execution.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] There are important features provided by Hadoop 3.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] For example, while there is one single *namenode* in Hadoop 2, Hadoop 3, enables having multiple name nodes, which solves the single point of failure problem.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] In Hadoop 3, there are containers working in principle of Docker, which reduces time spent on application development.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] One of the biggest changes is that Hadoop 3 decreases storage overhead with erasure coding.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Also, Hadoop 3 permits usage of GPU hardware within the cluster, which is a very substantial benefit to execute deep learning algorithms on a Hadoop cluster.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The HDFS is not restricted to MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] It can be used for other applications, many of which are under development at Apache.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] The list includes the HBase database, the Apache Mahout machine learning system, and the Apache Hive data warehouse.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Theoretically, Hadoop could be used for any workload that is batch-oriented rather than real-time, is very data-intensive, and benefits from parallel processing.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] It can also be used to complement a real-time system, such as lambda architecture, Apache Storm, Flink, and Spark Streaming.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Inc. launched what they claimed was the world's largest Hadoop production application.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Search Webmap is a Hadoop application that runs on a Linux cluster with more than 10,000 cores and produced data that was used in every Yahoo! web search query.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] There are multiple Hadoop clusters at Yahoo! and no HDFS file systems or MapReduce jobs are split across multiple data centers.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Every Hadoop cluster node bootstraps the Linux image, including the Hadoop distribution.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Work that the clusters perform is known to include the index calculations for the Yahoo! search engine.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] In June 2009, Yahoo! made the source code of its Hadoop version available to the open-source community.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] In 2010, Facebook claimed that they had the largest Hadoop cluster in the world with 21 PB of storage.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] In June 2012, they announced the data had grown to 100 PB and later that year they announced that the data was growing by roughly half a PB per day.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] As of 2013, Hadoop adoption had become widespread: more than half of the Fortune 50 companies used Hadoop.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] Influential papers on the birth, growth, and curation of Hadoop and big data processing include: Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat (2004) MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters, Google.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] This paper inspired Doug Cutting to develop an open-source implementation of the Map-Reduce framework.
[src:apache-avro/apache-hadoop] He named it Hadoop, after his son's toy elephant.
